      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Read this entire manual before assembly or use.</strong> Failure to follow safety instructions can result in serious injury or death.
      </div>

      <h3>Safety Symbols</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>DANGER:</strong> A potentially hazardous situation which, if not avoided, could result in death or serious injury.</li>
        <li><strong>WARNING:</strong> A potentially hazardous situation which, if not avoided, could result in death or serious injury.</li>
        <li><strong>CAUTION:</strong> A potentially hazardous situation which, if not avoided, may result in minor or moderate injury.</li>
        <li><strong>NOTICE:</strong> A helpful tip from the technical staff.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>General Safety Guidelines</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Read and understand the owner's manual before using the machine.</li>
        <li>Only trained or supervised operators should use this machine. Lock out or disconnect power when not in use, especially around children.</li>
        <li>Do not use in wet, cluttered, or poorly lit areas.</li>
        <li>Full mental alertness is required. Never operate under the influence of drugs or alcohol, when tired, or when distracted.</li>
        <li>Only qualified service personnel should perform electrical installation or repair.</li>
        <li>Always disconnect power before making adjustments, changing tooling, or servicing.</li>
        <li>Always wear ANSI-approved safety glasses or a face shield.</li>
        <li>Do not wear loose clothing, gloves, jewelry, or neckties. Tie back long hair. Wear non-slip footwear.</li>
        <li>Always wear a NIOSH-approved respirator to protect against hazardous dust.</li>
        <li>Always wear hearing protection when operating the machine.</li>
        <li>Remove adjusting keys and wrenches before starting the machine.</li>
        <li>Use the correct tool for the job. Never make unapproved modifications.</li>
        <li>Keep proper footing and balance. Do not overreach.</li>
        <li>Keep children and bystanders at a safe distance.</li>
        <li>Ensure guards and covers are properly installed and working before operation.</li>
        <li>Do not force the machine. It works better and more safely at its designed rate.</li>
        <li>Never stand on the machine.</li>
        <li>Verify the machine is stable and mobile base (if used) is locked before starting.</li>
        <li>Never leave the machine running while unattended.</li>
        <li>Follow all maintenance instructions and lubrication schedules.</li>
        <li>Regularly inspect for damaged, loose, or wrongly adjusted parts. Do not operate with damaged parts.</li>
        <li>When disconnecting, grab and pull the plug &mdash; not the cord.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Jointer-Specific Safety</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Kickback:</strong> Always use push blocks and safety glasses. Never stand in the kickback zone &mdash; the path directly through the end of the infeed table.</li>
        <li><strong>Cutterhead alignment:</strong> Keep the top edge of the outfeed table aligned with the cutterhead insert at Top Dead Center (TDC) to reduce kickback risk.</li>
        <li><strong>Push blocks:</strong> The cutterhead is extremely dangerous. Never pass your hands over it. Always use push blocks for face jointing. Hands must never be closer than 3 inches to the cutterhead.</li>
        <li><strong>Supporting the work:</strong> Only make cuts when the workpiece is stable. Never attempt to cut unstable planks.</li>
        <li><strong>Cutting depth:</strong> Never exceed the maximum cutting depth (1/8"). Take several small cuts rather than large ones.</li>
        <li><strong>Direction of cut:</strong> Always joint with the grain. Jointing against the grain or end grain is dangerous and causes chatter or chip-out.</li>
        <li><strong>Guards:</strong> Always use the guards. If removal is required (e.g., rabbeting), replace them immediately after.</li>
        <li><strong>Cutting direction:</strong> Only cut from the infeed table to the outfeed table. Always complete the cut &mdash; do not stop the wood until it has cleared the cutterhead completely.</li>
        <li><strong>Stock:</strong> Only use good lumber. Inspect for staples, nails, loose knots, and metal. These will damage the cutterhead and could cause injury or fire.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Electrical Safety</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Electrocution, fire, shock, or equipment damage may occur if the machine is not properly grounded and connected.</strong> Never run the machine in wet or damp conditions. Running on a different voltage than specified will damage the machine.
      </div>

      <h3>Motor Specifications</h3>
      <p>The main motor is 3 HP, wired for 220V, Single-Phase, 60 Hz, AC current with a NEMA 6-20P plug for North America. Confirm your motor electrical configuration and plug before connecting power. Ensure the starter and switches are in the "OFF" position before connecting.</p>

      <h3>Power Supply</h3>
      <p>A separate electrical circuit should be used for the machine: 220V, 1-Phase, 15 Amp minimum. Extension cords are not recommended. If one must be used, use only 3-wire cords with 3-prong grounding plugs heavy enough to carry the current.</p>

      <h3>Grounding</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-jx8/p09_01.jpg" alt="Grounding method A — receptacle with nominal rating less than 150V" />
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-jx8/p09_02.jpg" alt="Grounding method B — 150V receptacle with adapter" />
        <img src="/manuals/laguna-jx8/p09_03.jpg" alt="Grounding method C — 150-250V receptacle" />
      </div>
      <p>The machine is equipped with an electric cord having an equipment-grounding conductor and a grounding plug. The plug must be plugged into a matching outlet properly installed and grounded per local codes. Do not modify the plug. The green (or green with yellow stripes) conductor is the equipment-grounding conductor.</p>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>This machine must be grounded while in use to protect the operator from electric shock.</strong> If you are not sure the receptacle is properly grounded, have a qualified electrician check it.
      </div>

